        "subtopic": "English Overview",
        "content": "• India has a rich network of wildlife sanctuaries aimed at protecting flora and fauna.\n• As of 2025, there are around 573 wildlife sanctuaries in India.\n• These sanctuaries cover an area of approximately 122,500 sq. km, about 3.7% of India’s total geographical area.\n• Wildlife sanctuaries protect endangered species such as Bengal Tiger, Asiatic Lion, Snow Leopard, One-Horned Rhinoceros, and Indian Elephant.\n• They are also important for ecological balance, eco-tourism, and conservation education."
